 the window object serves as the overseer of the entire browser window. It grants control over actions like opening new tabs or windows, establishing timers for events, and managing cookies. Secondly, the document object acts as a meticulous librarian for the web page's content. It facilitates the retrieval and modification of all page elements, including text, images, and buttons, essentially serving as the bridge between your JavaScript code and the web page's structure. Lastly, the screen object functions as a source of information about the user's device, supplying details such as screen dimensions. This proves invaluable for ensuring that your web page displays effectively and functions seamlessly across various devices, ranging from small smartphones to large desktop monitors. These three objects are pivotal tools in the arsenal of web developers, enabling them to create interactive and responsive web applications.